{"title_page": "Football Australia (sporting federation)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{National football association\n| Logo               = Football Australia logo.png\n| Founded            = March 2012 ''inactive from June 2012''\n| FIFA affiliation   = \n| Region             = \n| Region affiliation = \n| President          = [[Clive Palmer (businessman)|Clive Palmer]]\n| CEO                = [[Archie Fraser]]\n| Website            = \n}}\n'''Football Australia''' was a rebel organisation for the sport of [[Soccer in Australia]] and operated without any international affiliates. It was founded in 2012 by [[Australia]]n business man [[Clive Palmer (businessman)|Clive Palmer]] after having his [[Gold Coast United]] [[A-League]] license revoked by the [[Football Federation Australia|FFA]]. [[Archie Fraser]] was the most recent of Football Australia and [[Clive Palmer]] was chairman. Football Australia's last public activity was in June 2012 and the organisation is presumed to be defunct.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://footballofaustralia.com/fas-national-public-inquiry-report-released-2/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=28 April 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120718233400/http://footballofaustralia.com/fas-national-public-inquiry-report-released-2/ |archive-date=18 July 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==History==\nOn 1 March 2012 Football Australia was launched by [[Australia]]n mining magnate [[Clive Palmer (businessman)|Clive Palmer]] with the slogan \"We Kick Harder\".<ref>http://www.theage.com.au/sport/a-league/we-kick-harder--clive-palmer-sets-up-rebel-football-organisation-20120301-1u5dn.html?skin=text-only</ref> It was originally announced that it was intended that the new federation would form a breakaway league and eventually replace the [[Football Federation Australia|FFA]] and oversee football at a grassroots level and senior level.<ref>http://www.theaustralian.com.au/sport/football/rebel-clive-palmers-bid-to-split-soccer/story-fn63e0vj-1226286624702</ref> However, Palmer and FA's newly appointed chief executive, former [[A-League]] chief [[Archie Fraser]], said the organisation was not necessarily out to topple the FFA but would act as watchdog and forum for ideas in the sport.<ref>http://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/6509939/Clive-Palmer-sets-up-rebel-football-organisation</ref> It planned to publish papers, hold press conferences, seek opinions, lobby the government, lobby the FFA for a better outcome for Australians and the game in Australia.<ref>http://www.theaustralian.com.au/sport/football/rebel-clive-palmers-bid-to-split-soccer/story-fn63e0vj-1226286624702</ref>\n\nSoon after the announcement many [[A-League]] club published statements rubbishing Palmer's new venture. [[Melbourne Heart]] CEO Scott Munn stated \"Our position is clear - we've signed a clubs participation agreement to enter the [[A-League]] run and operated by [[Football Federation Australia]]\" whilst [[Perth Glory]] owner [[Tony Sage]] declined to comment after previously supporting Clive Palmer. Sources from [[Sydney FC]] and [[Brisbane Roar]] also confirmed their intention of staying with the [[Football Federation Australia|FFA]].<ref>http://www.theaustralian.com.au/sport/football/rebel-clive-palmers-bid-to-split-soccer/story-fn63e0vj-1226286624702</ref>\n\nIt was also reported that Palmer tried to persuade a number of young [[Gold Coast United]] players to defect and sign contracts with a proposed rebel competition however a number of senior players intervened.<ref>http://www.foxsports.com.au/football/a-league/clive-palmer-reportedly-tried-to-lure-young-players-to-rebel-competition-before-late-intervention/story-e6frf4gl-1226286883895</ref>\n\nOn 2 March 2012 both the AFC{{Clarify|date=May 2014}} and [[FIFA]] publicly released a statement supporting [[Football Federation Australia]] saying that FIFA will only recognise one governing body in each FIFA affiliated nation and went on to say that \"FIFA will continue its close cooperation with the FFA, however, we will also continue to monitor the situation\".<ref>http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/sport/soccer/fifa-backs-ffa-and-frank-lowy-in-further-blow-to-rebel-gold-coast-united-clive-palmer/story-e6frey4r-1226287019383</ref>\n\nOn 13 March 2012 the federation launched a national commission of inquiry designed to hear submissions on ways to improve the sport\u2019s administration and development. It was announced that the federation will hold hearings in Townsville, Newcastle, Canberra, Sydney, Melbourne, Hobart, Adelaide and Perth. The hearings are to be conducted by former president of [[Football federation South Australia|FFSA]] Gary Collis with former [[Gold Coast United]] footballer [[Steve Fitzsimmons]] appointed secretary to the commission.<ref>http://www.theaustralian.com.au/sport/clive-palmers-soccer-body-announces-national-inquiry/story-e6frg7mf-1226298401705</ref> A limited release of the inquiry occurred on 2 June 2012<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://footballofaustralia.com/fas-national-public-inquiry-report-released-2/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=28 April 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120718233400/http://footballofaustralia.com/fas-national-public-inquiry-report-released-2/ |archive-date=18 July 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> but since then Football Australia has become inactive. The organisation's [[Twitter]] account was last active in June 2012 and the group's website domain name has not been re-registered.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Soccer in Australia]]\n*[[Football Federation Australia]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n\n[[Category:Soccer governing bodies in Australia]]\n[[Category:Sports organizations established in 2012]]\n[[Category:2012 establishments in Australia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{National football association\n| Logo               = Football Australia logo.png\n| Founded            = March 2012 ''inactive from June 2012''\n| FIFA affiliation   = \n| Region             = \n| Region affiliation = \n| President          = [[Clive Palmer (businessman)|Clive Palmer]]\n| CEO                = [[Archie Fraser]]\n| Website            = \n}}\n'''Football Australia''' was a rebel organisation for the sport of [[Soccer in Australia]] and operated without any international affiliates. It was founded in 2012 by [[Australia]]n business man [[Clive Palmer (businessman)|Clive Palmer]] after having his [[Gold Coast United]] [[A-League]] license revoked by the [[Football Federation Australia|FFA]]. [[Archie Fraser]] was the most recent of Football Australia and [[Clive Palmer (businessman)|Clive Palmer]] was chairman. Football Australia's last public activity was in June 2012 and the organisation is presumed to be defunct.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://footballofaustralia.com/fas-national-public-inquiry-report-released-2/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=28 April 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120718233400/http://footballofaustralia.com/fas-national-public-inquiry-report-released-2/ |archive-date=18 July 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==History==\nOn 1 March 2012 Football Australia was launched by [[Australia]]n mining magnate [[Clive Palmer (businessman)|Clive Palmer]] with the slogan \"We Kick Harder\".<ref>http://www.theage.com.au/sport/a-league/we-kick-harder--clive-palmer-sets-up-rebel-football-organisation-20120301-1u5dn.html?skin=text-only</ref> It was originally announced that it was intended that the new federation would form a breakaway league and eventually replace the [[Football Federation Australia|FFA]] and oversee football at a grassroots level and senior level.<ref>http://www.theaustralian.com.au/sport/football/rebel-clive-palmers-bid-to-split-soccer/story-fn63e0vj-1226286624702</ref> However, Palmer and FA's newly appointed chief executive, former [[A-League]] chief [[Archie Fraser]], said the organisation was not necessarily out to topple the FFA but would act as watchdog and forum for ideas in the sport.<ref>http://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/6509939/Clive-Palmer-sets-up-rebel-football-organisation</ref> It planned to publish papers, hold press conferences, seek opinions, lobby the government, lobby the FFA for a better outcome for Australians and the game in Australia.<ref>http://www.theaustralian.com.au/sport/football/rebel-clive-palmers-bid-to-split-soccer/story-fn63e0vj-1226286624702</ref>\n\nSoon after the announcement many [[A-League]] club published statements rubbishing Palmer's new venture. [[Melbourne Heart]] CEO Scott Munn stated \"Our position is clear - we've signed a clubs participation agreement to enter the [[A-League]] run and operated by [[Football Federation Australia]]\" whilst [[Perth Glory]] owner [[Tony Sage]] declined to comment after previously supporting Clive Palmer. Sources from [[Sydney FC]] and [[Brisbane Roar]] also confirmed their intention of staying with the [[Football Federation Australia|FFA]].<ref>http://www.theaustralian.com.au/sport/football/rebel-clive-palmers-bid-to-split-soccer/story-fn63e0vj-1226286624702</ref>\n\nIt was also reported that Palmer tried to persuade a number of young [[Gold Coast United]] players to defect and sign contracts with a proposed rebel competition however a number of senior players intervened.<ref>http://www.foxsports.com.au/football/a-league/clive-palmer-reportedly-tried-to-lure-young-players-to-rebel-competition-before-late-intervention/story-e6frf4gl-1226286883895</ref>\n\nOn 2 March 2012 both the AFC{{Clarify|date=May 2014}} and [[FIFA]] publicly released a statement supporting [[Football Federation Australia]] saying that FIFA will only recognise one governing body in each FIFA affiliated nation and went on to say that \"FIFA will continue its close cooperation with the FFA, however, we will also continue to monitor the situation\".<ref>http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/sport/soccer/fifa-backs-ffa-and-frank-lowy-in-further-blow-to-rebel-gold-coast-united-clive-palmer/story-e6frey4r-1226287019383</ref>\n\nOn 13 March 2012 the federation launched a national commission of inquiry designed to hear submissions on ways to improve the sport\u2019s administration and development. It was announced that the federation will hold hearings in Townsville, Newcastle, Canberra, Sydney, Melbourne, Hobart, Adelaide and Perth. The hearings are to be conducted by former president of [[Football federation South Australia|FFSA]] Gary Collis with former [[Gold Coast United]] footballer [[Steve Fitzsimmons]] appointed secretary to the commission.<ref>http://www.theaustralian.com.au/sport/clive-palmers-soccer-body-announces-national-inquiry/story-e6frg7mf-1226298401705</ref> A limited release of the inquiry occurred on 2 June 2012<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://footballofaustralia.com/fas-national-public-inquiry-report-released-2/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=28 April 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120718233400/http://footballofaustralia.com/fas-national-public-inquiry-report-released-2/ |archive-date=18 July 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> but since then Football Australia has become inactive. The organisation's [[Twitter]] account was last active in June 2012 and the group's website domain name has not been re-registered.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Soccer in Australia]]\n*[[Football Federation Australia]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n\n[[Category:Soccer governing bodies in Australia]]\n[[Category:Sports organizations established in 2012]]\n[[Category:2012 establishments in Australia]]\n", "name_user": "WDM10", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Football_Australia_(sporting_federation)"}
{"title_page": "Mario Dela\u0161", "text_new": "{{short description|Croatian basketball player}}\n{{distinguish|Mario Dela\u010d}}\n{{Infobox basketball biography\n| name         = Mario Dela\u0161\n| image        = \n| image size   = \n| caption      =\n| position     = [[Power forward (basketball)|Power forward]] / [[Center (basketball)|Center]] \n| height_ft    = 6\n| height_in    = 9.5\n| weight_lbs   = 227\n| league       = [[Serie A2 Basket]]\n| team         = XL Extralight Montegranaro\n| number       = \n| nationality  = Croatian\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1990|01|16}}\n| birth_place  = [[Split, Croatia|Split]], [[Socialist Republic of Croatia|SR Croatia]], [[Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia|SFR Yugoslavia]]\n| college      = \n| draft_year   = 2012\n| career_start = 2006\n| career_end   = \n| years1       = 2006\u20132010\n| team1        = [[KK Split|Split]]\n| years2       = 2010\u20132013\n| team2        = [[BC \u017dalgiris|\u017dalgiris]]\n| years3       = 2010\n| team3        = \u2192[[KK Cibona|Cibona]]\n| years4       = 2010\u20132011\n| team4        = \u2192[[BC \u0160iauliai]]\n| years5       = 2011\u20132012\n| team5        = \u2192[[BC Baltai]]\n| years6       = 2013\u20132014\n| team6        = [[Obradoiro CAB]]\n| years7       = 2014\u20132015\n| team7        = [[KK Cedevita|Cedevita]]\n| years8       = 2016\n| team8        = [[BC Kalev/Cramo|Kalev/Cramo]]\n| years9       = 2016\u20132018\n| team9        = [[Orlandina Basket]]\n| years10      = 2018\n| team10       = [[Pallacanestro Varese]]\n| years11      = 2018\u20132019\n| team11       = [[Egis K\u00f6rmend]]\n| years12      = 2019\u20132020\n| team12       = Split\n| years13      = 2020\u2013present\n| team13       = XL Extralight Montegranaro\n| highlights    = \n* [[Baltic Basketball League|Baltic League]] champion ([[Baltic League 2009\u201310|2010]])\n* 2\u00d7 [[Lithuanian Basketball League|Lithuanian League]] champion ([[2011-12 LKL season|2012]], [[2012\u201313 LKL season|2013]])\n* [[A-1 Liga|Croatian League]] champion ([[2014\u201315 A-1 League|2015]])\n* [[Korvpalli Meistriliiga|Estonian League]] champion ([[2015\u201316 KML season|2016]])\n* [[Kre\u0161imir \u0106osi\u0107 Cup|Croatian Cup]] winner (2015)\n* [[A-1 Liga|Croatian League]] All-Star (2010)\n* [[Lithuanian Basketball League|Lithuanian League]] All-Star ([[2013 LKL All-Star Game|2013]])\n* [[FIBA Under-19 World Cup MVP]] ([[2009 FIBA Under-19 World Championship|2009]])\n| medal_templates = \n{{MedalSport | Men\u2019s [[basketball]]}}\n{{MedalCountry|{{CRO}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FIBA Under-19 World Championship|World U-19 Championship]]}}\n{{MedalBronze| [[2009 FIBA Under-19 World Championship|2009 New Zealand]] | [[Croatia men's national under-19 basketball team|U-19 Team]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FIBA Europe Under-18 Championship|European U-18 Championship]]}}\n{{MedalBronze| [[2008 FIBA Europe Under-18 Championship|2008 Greece]] | [[Croatia men's national under-18 basketball team|U-18 Team]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Mario Dela\u0161''' (born January 16, 1990) is a Croatian professional [[basketball]] player for [[XL Extralight Montegranaro]] of the Italian second-tier [[Serie A2 Basket|Serie A2]]. He is a 2.07 m (6'9 {{1/2}}\") tall [[power forward (basketball)|power forward]] / [[center (basketball)|center]].<ref>[http://bgbasket.com/en/player.php?id=14970&act=player_career Mario Delas | #17 | PF/C.]</ref>\n\n==Professional career==\nMario Dela\u0161 made his professional debut in [[KK Split]], during the 2006\u201307 season. In January 2010, he signed a contract with [[BC \u017dalgiris]] for the next three-and-half seasons.<ref>[http://www.euroleague.net/news/i/65097/180 Zalgiris inks prospect Mario Delas]</ref> During the 2010\u201311 season, he was [[loan (sports)|loaned]] to [[KK Cibona]]<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.euroleague.net/euroleaguenews/transactions/2010-11-signings/i/74739/4465/cibona-welcomes-mario-delas | title = CIBONA welcomes Mario Delas | accessdate = 2010-08-20 | publisher = euroleague.net}}</ref> and [[BC \u0160iauliai]]. He spent most of the 2011\u201312 season on loan in the \u017dalgiris subsidiary [[BC Baltai]], returning to the \u017dalgiris team in March 2013. He signed with [[Obradoiro CAB]] in the summer of 2013.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.hrsport.net/vijesti/463777/kosarka-spanjolska/mario-delas-u-spanjolskoj-dogovoren-prijelaz-u-blusens-monbus/ | title = Mario Dela\u0161 u \u0160panjolskoj, dogovoren prijelaz u Blusens Monbus |date = 2013-07-13| accessdate = 2013-09-26 | publisher = hrsport.net|language = Croatian}}</ref> On June 30, 2014, he signed a multi-year deal with [[KK Cedevita|Cedevita Zagreb]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Mario Dela\u0161 i Fran Pilepi\u0107 u Cedeviti, ostaje i Marko Tomas|url=http://www.kkcedevita.hr/vijesti/tabid/86/id/22726/mario-dela-i-fran-pilepi-u-cedeviti-ostaje-i-marko-tomas.aspx#.U7GITkBv7Fw|language=Croatian|accessdate=June 30, 2014|publisher=kkcedevita.hr|date=June 30, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140706183515/http://www.kkcedevita.hr/vijesti/tabid/86/id/22726/mario-dela-i-fran-pilepi-u-cedeviti-ostaje-i-marko-tomas.aspx#.U7GITkBv7Fw|archive-date=July 6, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> In the first days of 2016, after spending the first half of the 2015\u201316 season in Cedevita, without playing a single minute, he moved to the Estonian side [[Kalev/Cramo]] for the rest of the season.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mario Dela\u0161 u doprvaku Estonije|url=http://crosarka.com/dijaspora/mario-delas-u-doprvaku-estonije-126730|publisher=crosarka.hr|language=Croatian|date=2 January 2016}}</ref> On September 19, 2016, he signed with the Italian [[Lega Basket Serie A|Serie A]] club [[Orlandina Basket]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Mario Delas inks with Orlandina Basket|url=http://www.sportando.com/en/italy/serie-a/212170/mario-delas-inks-with-orlandina-basket.html|accessdate=20 September 2016|work=Sportando.com|date=19 September 2016}}</ref> On February 14, 2018, he parted ways with Orlandina.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mario Delas, Orlandina part ways|url=https://sportando.basketball/en/italy/serie-a/264904/mario-delas-orlandina-part-ways.html|accessdate=14 February 2018|work=Sportando.com|date=14 February 2018}}</ref> Two days later, he signed with [[Pallacanestro Varese]] for the remainder of the season.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mario Delas inks with Pallacanestro Varese|url=https://sportando.basketball/en/italy/serie-a/265079/mario-delas-inks-with-pallacanestro-varese.html|accessdate=17 February 2018|work=Sportando.com|date=17 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn December, 2019 Dela\u0161 returned to [[KK Split|Split]] of the [[Croatian Basketball League|Croatian League]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Na Gripe stiglo poznato ime: Mario Dela\u0161 nakon 10 godina ponovno u KK Splitu|url=https://www.slobodnadalmacija.hr/sport/kosarka/clanak/id/638633/na-gripe-stiglo-poznato-ime-mario-delas-nakon-10-godina-ponovno-u-kk-splitu|language=Croatian|date=16 December 2019}}</ref> After spending a month and playing only four games for Split, in January 2020, Dela\u0161 moved to [[XL Extralight Montegranaro]] of the Italian second-tier [[Serie A2 Basket|Serie A2]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Mario Dela\u0161 napustio Split, ve\u0107 ima novi klub|url=https://www.germanijak.hr/vijesti/mario-delas-napustio-split-vec-ima-novi-klub/70644|language=Croatian|work=germanijak.hr|date=20 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==National team career==\nDela\u0161 represented his country's junior national teams in Under-16, Under-18, Under-19 and Under-20 competitions, winning bronze medals at the [[2008 FIBA Europe Under-18 Championship]], and at the [[2009 FIBA Under-19 World Championship|2009 FIBA Under-19 World Cup]]. He was selected to the All-Tournament Teams of both championships, and also won [[FIBA Under-19 World Cup MVP|the MVP award]] in the latter tournament, averaging 20 points per game. His first call-up to the senior men's [[Croatian national basketball team]] came in 2013. He was a part of the Croatian team that took 4th place at the [[2013 EuroBasket]], where he played only a minor role in his team's success.\n\n==Personal life==\nHe is the younger brother of [[Ante Dela\u0161]], who is also a professional basketball player, and with whom he played with on [[KK Split|Split]], [[KK Cedevita|Cedevita]] and the [[Croatian national basketball team]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.aba-liga.com/League/Player.aspx?id=832 Mario Dela\u0161] at aba-liga.com\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20131004224248/http://www.acb.com/jugador.php?id=H08 Mario Dela\u0161] at acb.com {{in lang|es}}\n* [http://www.euroleague.net/competition/players/showplayer?pcode=002504 Mario Dela\u0161] at euroleague.net\n* [http://www.fibaeurope.com/cid_KNce8jInH7Qj1EsyH5rjn2.pageID_IJtcDwZlHjwTudePzRDrS0.compID_8aYeHlfuGF-mF5IqO8aFH1.season_2008.roundID_6072.teamID_2168.playerID_57978.html Mario Dela\u0161] at fibaeurope.com\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20131020104724/http://www.hks-cbf.hr/index.php/mario-delas#.UmKKNRAlUyM Mario Dela\u0161] at hks-cbf.hr\n* [https://basketball.realgm.com/player/Mario-Delas/Summary/25023 Mario Dela\u0161] at realGM\n\n{{FIBA Under-19 World Championship MVP}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Delas, Mario}}\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:ABA League players]]\n[[Category:BC Kalev/Cramo players]]\n[[Category:BC K\u00f6rmend players]]\n[[Category:BC \u0160iauliai players]]\n[[Category:BC \u017dalgiris players]]\n[[Category:Centers (basketball)]]\n[[Category:Croatian expatriate basketball people in Spain]]\n[[Category:Croatian expatriate sportspeople in Lithuania]]\n[[Category:Croatian men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:KK Cedevita players]]\n[[Category:KK Cibona players]]\n[[Category:KK Split players]]\n[[Category:Lega Basket Serie A players]]\n[[Category:Liga ACB players]]\n[[Category:LSU-Atletas basketball players]]\n[[Category:Obradoiro CAB players]]\n[[Category:Orlandina Basket players]]\n[[Category:Pallacanestro Varese players]]\n[[Category:Power forwards (basketball)]]\n[[Category:Expatriate basketball people in Estonia]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Croatian basketball player}}\n{{distinguish|Mario Dela\u010d}}\n{{Infobox basketball biography\n| name         = Mario Dela\u0161\n| image        = \n| image size   = \n| caption      =\n| position     = [[Power forward (basketball)|Power forward]] / [[Center (basketball)|Center]] \n| height_ft    = 6\n| height_in    = 9.5\n| weight_lbs   = 227\n| league       = [[Serie A2 Basket]]\n| team         = XL Extralight Montegranaro\n| number       = \n| nationality  = Croatian\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1990|01|16}}\n| birth_place  = [[Split, Croatia|Split]], [[Socialist Republic of Croatia|SR Croatia]], [[Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia|SFR Yugoslavia]]\n| college      = \n| draft_year   = 2012\n| career_start = 2006\n| career_end   = \n| years1       = 2006\u20132010\n| team1        = [[KK Split|Split]]\n| years2       = 2010\u20132013\n| team2        = [[BC \u017dalgiris|\u017dalgiris]]\n| years3       = 2010\n| team3        = \u2192[[KK Cibona|Cibona]]\n| years4       = 2010\u20132011\n| team4        = \u2192[[BC \u0160iauliai]]\n| years5       = 2011\u20132012\n| team5        = \u2192[[BC Baltai]]\n| years6       = 2013\u20132014\n| team6        = [[Obradoiro CAB]]\n| years7       = 2014\u20132015\n| team7        = [[KK Cedevita|Cedevita]]\n| years8       = 2016\n| team8        = [[BC Kalev/Cramo|Kalev/Cramo]]\n| years9       = 2016\u20132018\n| team9        = [[Orlandina Basket]]\n| years10      = 2018\n| team10       = [[Pallacanestro Varese]]\n| years11      = 2018\u20132019\n| team11       = [[Egis K\u00f6rmend]]\n| years12      = 2019\u20132020\n| team12       = Split\n| years13      = 2020\u2013present\n| team13       = XL Extralight Montegranaro\n| highlights    = \n* [[Baltic Basketball League|Baltic League]] champion ([[Baltic League 2009\u201310|2010]])\n* 2\u00d7 [[Lithuanian Basketball League|Lithuanian League]] champion ([[2011-12 LKL season|2012]], [[2012\u201313 LKL season|2013]])\n* [[A-1 Liga|Croatian League]] champion ([[2014\u201315 A-1 League|2015]])\n* [[Korvpalli Meistriliiga|Estonian League]] champion ([[2015\u201316 KML season|2016]])\n* [[Kre\u0161imir \u0106osi\u0107 Cup|Croatian Cup]] winner (2015)\n* [[A-1 Liga|Croatian League]] All-Star (2010)\n* [[Lithuanian Basketball League|Lithuanian League]] All-Star ([[2013 LKL All-Star Game|2013]])\n* [[FIBA Under-19 World Cup MVP]] ([[2009 FIBA Under-19 World Championship|2009]])\n| medal_templates = \n{{MedalSport | Men\u2019s [[basketball]]}}\n{{MedalCountry|{{CRO}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FIBA Under-19 World Championship|World U-19 Championship]]}}\n{{MedalBronze| [[2009 FIBA Under-19 World Championship|2009 New Zealand]] | [[Croatia men's national under-19 basketball team|U-19 Team]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FIBA Europe Under-18 Championship|European U-18 Championship]]}}\n{{MedalBronze| [[2008 FIBA Europe Under-18 Championship|2008 Greece]] | [[Croatia men's national under-18 basketball team|U-18 Team]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Mario Dela\u0161''' (born January 16, 1990) is a Croatian professional [[basketball]] player for [[XL Extralight Montegranaro]] of the Italian second-tier [[Serie A2 Basket|Serie A2]]. He is a 2.07 m (6'9 {{1/2}}\") tall [[power forward (basketball)|power forward]] / [[center (basketball)|center]].<ref>[http://bgbasket.com/en/player.php?id=14970&act=player_career Mario Delas | #17 | PF/C.]</ref>\n\n==Professional career==\nMario Dela\u0161 made his professional debut in [[KK Split]], during the 2006\u201307 season. In January 2010, he signed a contract with [[BC \u017dalgiris]] for the next three-and-half seasons.<ref>[http://www.euroleague.net/news/i/65097/180 Zalgiris inks prospect Mario Delas]</ref> During the 2010\u201311 season, he was [[loan (sports)|loaned]] to [[KK Cibona]]<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.euroleague.net/euroleaguenews/transactions/2010-11-signings/i/74739/4465/cibona-welcomes-mario-delas | title = CIBONA welcomes Mario Delas | accessdate = 2010-08-20 | publisher = euroleague.net}}</ref> and [[BC \u0160iauliai]]. He spent most of the 2011\u201312 season on loan in the \u017dalgiris subsidiary [[BC Baltai]], returning to the \u017dalgiris team in March 2013. He signed with [[Obradoiro CAB]] in the summer of 2013.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.hrsport.net/vijesti/463777/kosarka-spanjolska/mario-delas-u-spanjolskoj-dogovoren-prijelaz-u-blusens-monbus/ | title = Mario Dela\u0161 u \u0160panjolskoj, dogovoren prijelaz u Blusens Monbus |date = 2013-07-13| accessdate = 2013-09-26 | publisher = hrsport.net|language = Croatian}}</ref> On June 30, 2014, he signed a multi-year deal with [[KK Cedevita|Cedevita Zagreb]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Mario Dela\u0161 i Fran Pilepi\u0107 u Cedeviti, ostaje i Marko Tomas|url=http://www.kkcedevita.hr/vijesti/tabid/86/id/22726/mario-dela-i-fran-pilepi-u-cedeviti-ostaje-i-marko-tomas.aspx#.U7GITkBv7Fw|language=Croatian|accessdate=June 30, 2014|publisher=kkcedevita.hr|date=June 30, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140706183515/http://www.kkcedevita.hr/vijesti/tabid/86/id/22726/mario-dela-i-fran-pilepi-u-cedeviti-ostaje-i-marko-tomas.aspx#.U7GITkBv7Fw|archive-date=July 6, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> In the first days of 2016, after spending the first half of the 2015\u201316 season in Cedevita, without playing a single minute, he moved to the Estonian side [[Kalev/Cramo]] for the rest of the season.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mario Dela\u0161 u doprvaku Estonije|url=http://crosarka.com/dijaspora/mario-delas-u-doprvaku-estonije-126730|publisher=crosarka.hr|language=Croatian|date=2 January 2016}}</ref> On September 19, 2016, he signed with the Italian [[Lega Basket Serie A|Serie A]] club [[Orlandina Basket]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Mario Delas inks with Orlandina Basket|url=http://www.sportando.com/en/italy/serie-a/212170/mario-delas-inks-with-orlandina-basket.html|accessdate=20 September 2016|work=Sportando.com|date=19 September 2016}}</ref> On February 14, 2018, he parted ways with Orlandina.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mario Delas, Orlandina part ways|url=https://sportando.basketball/en/italy/serie-a/264904/mario-delas-orlandina-part-ways.html|accessdate=14 February 2018|work=Sportando.com|date=14 February 2018}}</ref> Two days later, he signed with [[Pallacanestro Varese]] for the remainder of the season.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mario Delas inks with Pallacanestro Varese|url=https://sportando.basketball/en/italy/serie-a/265079/mario-delas-inks-with-pallacanestro-varese.html|accessdate=17 February 2018|work=Sportando.com|date=17 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn December, 2019 Dela\u0161 returned to [[KK Split|Split]] of the [[Croatian Basketball League|Croatian League]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Na Gripe stiglo poznato ime: Mario Dela\u0161 nakon 10 godina ponovno u KK Splitu|url=https://www.slobodnadalmacija.hr/sport/kosarka/clanak/id/638633/na-gripe-stiglo-poznato-ime-mario-delas-nakon-10-godina-ponovno-u-kk-splitu|language=Croatian|date=16 December 2019}}</ref> After spending a month and playing only four games for Split, in Januray 2020, Dela\u0161 moved to [[XL Extralight Montegranaro]] of the Italian second-tier [[Serie A2 Basket|Serie A2]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Mario Dela\u0161 napustio Split, ve\u0107 ima novi klub|url=https://www.germanijak.hr/vijesti/mario-delas-napustio-split-vec-ima-novi-klub/70644|language=Croatian|work=germanijak.hr|date=20 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==National team career==\nDela\u0161 represented his country's junior national teams in Under-16, Under-18, Under-19 and Under-20 competitions, winning bronze medals at the [[2008 FIBA Europe Under-18 Championship]], and at the [[2009 FIBA Under-19 World Championship|2009 FIBA Under-19 World Cup]]. He was selected to the All-Tournament Teams of both championships, and also won [[FIBA Under-19 World Cup MVP|the MVP award]] in the latter tournament, averaging 20 points per game. His first call-up to the senior men's [[Croatian national basketball team]] came in 2013. He was a part of the Croatian team that took 4th place at the [[2013 EuroBasket]], where he played only a minor role in his team's success.\n\n==Personal life==\nHe is the younger brother of [[Ante Dela\u0161]], who is also a professional basketball player, and with whom he played with on [[KK Split|Split]], [[KK Cedevita|Cedevita]] and the [[Croatian national basketball team]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.aba-liga.com/League/Player.aspx?id=832 Mario Dela\u0161] at aba-liga.com\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20131004224248/http://www.acb.com/jugador.php?id=H08 Mario Dela\u0161] at acb.com {{in lang|es}}\n* [http://www.euroleague.net/competition/players/showplayer?pcode=002504 Mario Dela\u0161] at euroleague.net\n* [http://www.fibaeurope.com/cid_KNce8jInH7Qj1EsyH5rjn2.pageID_IJtcDwZlHjwTudePzRDrS0.compID_8aYeHlfuGF-mF5IqO8aFH1.season_2008.roundID_6072.teamID_2168.playerID_57978.html Mario Dela\u0161] at fibaeurope.com\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20131020104724/http://www.hks-cbf.hr/index.php/mario-delas#.UmKKNRAlUyM Mario Dela\u0161] at hks-cbf.hr\n* [https://basketball.realgm.com/player/Mario-Delas/Summary/25023 Mario Dela\u0161] at realGM\n\n{{FIBA Under-19 World Championship MVP}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Delas, Mario}}\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:ABA League players]]\n[[Category:BC Kalev/Cramo players]]\n[[Category:BC K\u00f6rmend players]]\n[[Category:BC \u0160iauliai players]]\n[[Category:BC \u017dalgiris players]]\n[[Category:Centers (basketball)]]\n[[Category:Croatian expatriate basketball people in Spain]]\n[[Category:Croatian expatriate sportspeople in Lithuania]]\n[[Category:Croatian men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:KK Cedevita players]]\n[[Category:KK Cibona players]]\n[[Category:KK Split players]]\n[[Category:Lega Basket Serie A players]]\n[[Ca